and will it work similarly if it loses focus because you switch to an entirely different window in hyprland? eg from ghostty/tmux/neovim to chrome ?

Yes, it will work—but the "chain of communication" is longer.

When you switch from your terminal (Ghostty) to Chrome in Hyprland, the focus events travel through several layers to reach Neovim. If any of these layers "drops the ball," it won't work.

Here is the path the signal takes:

Hyprland (Wayland Compositor) tells Ghostty it has lost focus.

Ghostty sends a "FocusOut" escape sequence to the application running inside it (tmux).

tmux receives that signal and, because you set focus-events on, it forwards that signal to the active pane (Neovim).

Neovim receives the signal and triggers FocusLost.

Why this is great in Hyprland
Because Hyprland is a tiling window manager, you’re often jumping between windows rapidly. Having this set up means:

Browser/Docs Sync: You can look at a tutorial in Chrome, then click back into your terminal, and Neovim will instantly refresh its syntax highlighting or diagnostics because it knows you're back.

Clipboard/Persistence: If you have an "auto-save on focus lost" script, your work is saved the second you move your mouse/focus to Chrome, ensuring that if you run a build script in another window, it’s using the latest code.

Troubleshooting the "Wayland Gap"
Sometimes Wayland compositors and terminals have "opinions" about focus. To ensure this works specifically for your setup:

Ghostty Check: Ghostty is quite modern and supports focus events natively, so you shouldn't need extra config there.

Verify in Neovim: You can test the "Global" focus switch (Ghostty → Chrome) using the same snippet from before:

Lua
vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd("FocusLost", {
    callback = function()
        print("Neovim lost focus to the OS!")
    end,
})
Switch to Chrome. If you switch back and see that message in your :messages history, the entire chain (Hyprland → Ghostty → tmux → Neovim) is working perfectly.

One small catch: Some older versions of tmux or specific TERM settings can eat these events. If it doesn't work, make sure your TERM inside tmux is set to tmux-256color or screen-256color.

